```
int maximum(int a, int b) {
    if (a > b) {
        return a;
    } else {
        return b;
    }
}
```

In this function, there are two return statements, but only one of them will be executed depending on the values of a and b. 

However, it is recommended to avoid having multiple return statements in a function as it can make the code harder to read and maintain. A single return statement at the end of the function is generally considered best practice.

This is generally true. Constant call by reference, also known as `const` reference, is often used in C++ when a parameter is an object whose value should not change in the function. This type of parameter passing offers the efficiency of call by reference, since the function does not need to create a copy of the object, and the safety of call by value, since the function cannot modify the original object. 

Using `const` reference can improve performance by avoiding the overhead of copying large objects when calling a function. Additionally, it provides a guarantee that the original value of the object will not be modified by the function. 

Here is an example:

```
void printObject(const Object& obj) {
    // do something with obj but cannot modify its value
}

int main() {
    Object o;
    printObject(o);
}
```

In this example, a constant reference to an `Object` is passed as a parameter to the `printObject()` function. The `const` keyword ensures that the function cannot modify the object's value. This is useful when working with complex objects that should not be modified by a function, as it provides protection against unintended changes.

